Here is an example of how to automatically generate a table of contents in LaTeX:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
...section content here...

\section{Methods}
...section content here... 

\section{Results}
...section content here...

\section{Discussion}
...section content here...

\end{document}

The key points are:

- Include the \usepackage{tocloft} command in the preamble to allow customization of the table of contents
- Add the \tableofcontents command where you want the table of contents to appear (usually at the beginning of the document)
- Use \section commands to divide the document into sections
- LaTeX automatically collects the sections and their page numbers and generates the table of contents based on the \section commands
- Run LaTeX twice to ensure the page numbers are correct and the table of contents is updated

The tocloft package allows further customization of the font, spacing, and style of the table of contents if desired. But the above shows the minimum working example.

